// SchedulerService — scored, readiness-aware agent selection contract.
//
// The task broker (or any dispatching caller) asks the scheduler for exactly
// ONE agent able to execute a capability, under an optional policy and hard
// constraints. The scheduler answers from its informer-backed view of Agent
// custom resources and returns the chosen agent together with a structured
// SelectionRationale explaining the decision.
//
// Design rationale: ADR-039 (CRD-native scheduler — the Agent CR is the
// single source of truth; the registry evolves into a stateless scheduler),
// ADR-040 (capability matching and scheduling intelligence stay Zynax-core),
// ADR-028 (expert targeting is strict — no fallback). This file is additive:
// AgentDef and CapabilityDef are reused from agent_registry.proto, whose
// RPCs are deprecated separately (deprecation in M8, removal in M9).
//
// Contract invariants:
//   1. SelectAgent returns exactly one agent or a gRPC error — never an
//      empty response and never more than one candidate.
//   2. capability_name is required; empty is rejected with INVALID_ARGUMENT.
//   3. No agent declares the capability → NOT_FOUND (with a machine-readable
//      reason in the status message).
//   4. Candidates exist but hard constraints, readiness, or the expert
//      target eliminate all of them → FAILED_PRECONDITION; the status
//      message names the first eliminating filter.
//   5. expert_target is strict (ADR-028): only agents declaring that expert
//      scope are eligible; when none qualifies the call fails rather than
//      falling back to a non-expert agent.
//   6. Metrics unavailability is never an error: selection degrades to
//      readiness-filtered round-robin and the rationale reports mode
//      SELECTION_MODE_DEGRADED_ROUND_ROBIN (ADR-039 §3).
//   7. The rationale is structured for machines and dashboards — callers
//      must not need to parse free text to learn why an agent won.

